Class AbstractSQLQueryFilterVisitor<R extends SQLRenderer<?>,P>

    R - the subclass of SQLRenderer the visitor returns

    StringSQLQueryFilterVisitor

    public abstract class AbstractSQLQueryFilterVisitor<R extends SQLRenderer<?>,P>
extends Object
implements org.forgerock.util.query.QueryFilterVisitor<R,P,org.forgerock.json.JsonPointer>
    An abstract QueryFilterVisitor to produce SQL via an SQLRenderer. Includes implementation patterns for the standard
    • >=
    • >
    • =
    • <
    • <=
    operators, along with the following implementations for QueryFilter's
    • contains : field LIKE '%value%'
    • startsWith : field LIKE 'value%'

    This implementation does not support extended-match.

    The implementer is responsible for implementing

    • visitValueAssertion(Object, String, org.forgerock.json.JsonPointer, Object) which handles the value assertions - x operand y for the standard operands
    • visitPresentFilter(Object, org.forgerock.json.JsonPointer) as "field present" can vary by database implementation (though typically "field IS NOT NULL" is chosen)
    • @{link #visitBooleanLiteralFilter(Object, boolean)} to express a boolean true or false in whatever SQL dialect is being used
    • @{link #visitNotFilter(Object, QueryFilter)} to negate the QueryFilter parameter
    • @{link #visitAndFilter(Object, List<QueryFilter>, Object)} to dictate how the composite function AND behaves
    • @{link #visitOrFilter(Object, List<QueryFilter>, Object)} to dictate how the composite function OR behaves

      • visitValueAssertion

        public abstract R visitValueAssertion(P parameters,
                                      String operand,
                                      org.forgerock.json.JsonPointer field,
                                      Object valueAssertion)
        A templating method that will generate the actual value assertion.

        Example: 

        
     ?_queryFilter=email+eq+"someone@example.com"
        is an QueryFilter stating the value assertion "email" equals "someone@example.com". The correct SQL for that may vary depending on database variant and schema definition. This method will be invoked as 
        
     return visitValueAssertion(parameters, "=", JsonPointer(/email), "someone@example.com");
        A possible implementation for the above example may be 
        
     return getDatabaseColumnFor("email") + "=" + ":email";
        The parameters argument is implementation-dependent as a way to store placeholder mapping throughout the query-filter visiting.
        Parameters:
        parameters - storage of parameter-substitutions for the value of the assertion
        operand - the operand used to compare
        field - the object field as a JsonPointer - implementations need to map this to an appropriate database column
        valueAssertion - the value in the assertion
        Returns:
        a query expression or clause
